Just cleared the Claude Certified Architect – Foundations exam.



Not going to just post the certificate and move on.



Here's what I actually learned — and what I think every developer

entering the AI space should understand before they write a single line

of agentic code:



1. Claude doesn't run anything. It just talks.

  Every interaction is an API call — you send text, it replies.

  When it wants to use a tool, it asks YOU to run it and bring

  back the result. The model has no hands. You are the hands.



2. An AI agent is just a loop.

  Claude thinks → requests a tool → you run it → return the result

  → Claude thinks again. This repeats until the job is done.

  That's it. That's the whole architecture everyone is building on.



3. Prompts fail. Code doesn't.

  If a step must ALWAYS happen, enforce it programmatically —

  not with instructions. A well-written prompt works 88% of the time.

  In production, that other 12% is real money, real errors, real users.



4. In multi-agent systems, agents are strangers to each other.

  They share zero memory. If Agent B needs what Agent A found,

  you copy it into Agent B's prompt yourself. Every time. No exceptions.

  Forgetting this is the #1 reason multi-agent systems produce

  incomplete, incoherent output.



5. The quality of a tool's description decides everything.

  Claude picks tools based on how they're described — not magic.

  A vague description means wrong tool calls. A precise one means

  reliable behaviour. This is where most production bugs actually live.



6. When you want structured output — force it, don't ask for it.

  Give Claude a JSON schema and make it fill the form. Mark fields

  nullable when data might be missing. Otherwise it'll hallucinate

  values to fill the gaps — confidently and silently.



7. Not all tasks deserve real-time processing.

  The Batch API is 50% cheaper and handles thousands of requests

  asynchronously. For nightly reports, weekly audits, bulk analysis —

  you're wasting money doing it any other way.



8. One misplaced config file can make your whole team invisible.

  Instructions stored at the user level stay on your machine.

  Your teammates are working completely blind and don't know it.



The deeper I went, the clearer it became — AI engineering isn't

about clever prompting. It's about building systems that fail

loudly, recover gracefully, and never silently do the wrong thing.



